{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592581"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:17:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:17:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15265"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15265"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0,0.03,0.9]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7956"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65194"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7956"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50631"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"6884"},{"type":"tags","id":"6887"},{"type":"tags","id":"8399"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21660"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65194"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gastro-oesophageal junction contains several important anatomical landmarks.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the Z-line?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contains only stratified squamous epithelium","Is found exclusively in the proximal oesophagus","Is located 5 cm above the diaphragm","Represents abnormal metaplastic change","The junction between squamous and columnar epithelium"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EZ-line\u003C/strong\u003E represents the junction between the squamous epithelium of the oesophagus and the columnar epithelium of the stomach. It is a normal anatomical landmark typically visible on endoscopy. (Image 1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Z-line is normally located at the gastro-oesophageal junction, not \u003Cstrong\u003E5 cm above the diaphragm\u003C/strong\u003E. It does not inherently represent \u003Cstrong\u003Eabnormal metaplastic change\u003C/strong\u003E, though displacement of the Z-line can occur in conditions like Barrett\u0027s oesophagus (Image 2). The Z-line does not contain only \u003Cstrong\u003Estratified squamous epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E - it is precisely where this transitions to columnar epithelium. It is not found in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eproximal oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E but rather at the distal end where the oesophagus meets the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Z-line (squamocolumnar junction) marks the transition between oesophageal squamous epithelium and gastric columnar epithelium.","The Z-line is a normal anatomical landmark visible on endoscopy at the gastro-oesophageal junction."],"references":["Yazaki E, Sifrim D. Anatomy and physiology of the esophageal body. Dis Esophagus. 2012 May;25(4):292-8. doi: 10.1111/j.1442-2050.2011.01180.x. Epub 2011 Mar 8. PMID: 21385283.","Chaudhry SR, Bordoni B. Anatomy, Thorax, Esophagus. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482513/","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons."]},"rel